This game has all the charm and polish that you'd expect from a Kairosoft game, but the game mechanics are a bit lacking. It takes a LONG time for the game to get rolling, and even when it does, you still spend most of your time waiting for the money to roll in.  One especially irritating thing is how the game handles paying your employees. You have to do it once a year in a single massive cash dump, rather than every month in much more manageable chunks.  I recommend Sushi Spinnery instead.

Doesn't measure up to Game Dev Story or Epic Astro Story. 1. There is almost nothing for me to actually do other than wait and watch the people walking around. Gets boring after the first few years. 2. Not enough information. I know which qualities certain customers like, but I can't see what qualities a certain type of food has unless I'm upgrading it. Am I expected to keep a side notebook with this kind of info? 3. The whole process of buying/finding ingredients and using them to upgrade dishes makes no logical sense. Why do I have to pay so much for a single chicken leg when it's obvious that I go through a bunch of them every day and pay considerably less to restock them? 4. The game makes a big deal about the fact that I have to pick my table type carefully, but I've never seen any options for that. The huge tables only go in the huge table slot, the single-person counters only go in the small slots, and the couches for the normal slots can seat 2 as easily as they seat 4. There's no reason not to fill your restaurant with couches.

Kairo makes the best games around, period. But this one is their least fun. The biggest problem is there's no "excitement" factor. In Dungeon Village you go on quests, anxious to find a new weapon or item, to fight newer and tougher monsters. Grand Prix + Pocket League: you get to watch your characters actually race or play a match.  In this game you just sit and watch, watch, and watch. Set your dishes and watch the people do their thing until the day is over or a notification pops up. Not much customization in terms of the dishes (besides stats), everything is straightforward in recipes so if you think you'll be able to create something wacky like pumpkin pasta then this isn't the game for you. Same with the restaurant layout, you can pick what tables you want but the spaces they go to are predetermined, so it's not like the other games that let you put what you want wherever you want.  Good game nonetheless. With a bit more freedom and some kind of exciting hook then it could've been better. I finished one run and don't have the heart for another.
